olitical consultant)|Rick Gates]], [[Paul Manafort]], the [[Embassy of Russia in Washington, D.C.|Russian Embassy in the United States]], and a Russian firm, Prevezon Alexander, LLC., involved with [[money laundering]].<ref name=NYT2018-10-17>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/17/business/treasury-leak-manafort.html|title=Treasury Official Charged With Leaking Bank Reports to Journalist|date=October 17, 2018|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|last=Flitter|first=Emily|access-date=October 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Sputnik2018-10-17>{{cite news|url=https://sputniknews.com/world/201810171068975250-us-treasury-butina/|title=US Treasury Adviser Charged With Leaking Info on Detained Russian Citizen Butina|date=October 17, 2018|agency=[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]]|access-date=October 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/politics/treasury-official-pleads-not-guilty-in-leaking-case|title=Treasury official pleads not guilty in leaking case|author=|date=January 31, 2019|website=WDIV|accessdate=January 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe government\u2019s decision to charge Dr. Edwards is significant as this appears to be the first criminal case based ''solely'' upon an unauthorized disclosure of a SAR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneylaunderingnews.com/2018/10/fincen-employee-charged-with-unlawful-disclosure-of-sars/|title=FinCEN Employee Charged with Unlawful Disclosure of SARs to Reporter|date=2018-10-24|website=Money Laundering Watch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> The criminal complaint against her contains a footnote that \"Edwards told the Interviewing Agents, in sum and substance, that she is a \u201c[[whistleblower]]\u201d and the government acknowledges she filed a whistleblower complaint and reached out to congressional staffers\". The footnote continues on to note that the whistleblower complaint filed was \"unrelated to the SARs disclosures.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/391067147/u-s-v-Natalie-Edwards-Complaint|title=u.s. v. Natalie Edwards Complaint|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Customs Service personnel]]\n[[Category:People associated with Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:Whistleblowers]]\n\n\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natalie_Edwards"}
{"title_page": "Patrick G. Eddington", "text_new": "'''Patrick Eddington''' is an American author, policy analyst in national security and civil liberties at the [[Cato Institute]], served as a [[CIA]] military [[Imagery analysis|imagery analyst]] ([[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency#National Photographic Interpretation Center .28NPIC.29|National Photographic Interpretation Center]]) from 1988\u20131996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/staff/patrick-g-eddington/|title=Patrick G. Eddington \u2013 The Intercept|work=theintercept.com|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure at the CIA, his analytical assignments included monitoring the breakup of the former [[Soviet Union]]; providing military assessments to policy makers on [[Iraq]]i and [[Iran]]ian conventional forces and coordinating the CIA's military targeting support to [[NATO]] during [[Operation Deliberate Force]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]] in 1995.\n\nEddington resigned in 1996 after working on the book ''Gassed in the Gulf: The Inside Story of the Pentagon-CIA Cover-up of Gulf War Syndrome'', in which he presented the claim of substantial evidence that American soldiers were exposed to chemical agents during the Persian Gulf War in 1991.\n\nHis CIA memoir, ''Long Strange Journey'', was published in 2011. In a 2011 interview with the Washington Post, Eddington accused the CIA of still withholding 1.5 million documents relevant to the Desert Storm malady known as [[gulf war syndrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/spy-talk/2011/02/ex-cia_analyst_patrcik_eddingt.html|title=SpyTalk - Ex-CIA analyst Patrick Eddington accuses agency of \u2018sitting on\u2019 Gulf War illness documents|work=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nEddington's opinion pieces have appeared in numerous of publications, including the ''[[Washington Post]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[Washington Times]]'', ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'', and the ''[[Army Times]]''. Eddington is a frequent commentator on national security issues for the [[Fox News Channel]], [[MSNBC]], [[SKY News]], [[CNN]], and other domestic and international television networks.\n\n== Books ==\n* ''Gassed in the Gulf: The Inside Story of the Pentagon-CIA Cover-up of Gulf War Syndrome'', August 1997, Insignia Publishing Company\n* ''Long Strange Journey: An Intelligence Memoir'', 2011\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.patrickeddington.com Eddington home page]\n*{{C-SPAN|Patrick Eddington}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eddington, Patrick G.}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People of the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Gulf War syndrome]]\n[[Category:American whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Patrick Eddington''' is an American author, policy analyst in national security and civil liberties at the [[Cato Institute]], served as a [[CIA]] military [[Imagery analysis|imagery analyst]] ([[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency#National Photographic Interpretation Center .28NPIC.29|National Photographic Interpretation Center]]) from 1988-1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/staff/patrick-g-eddington/|title=Patrick G. Eddington \u2013 The Intercept|work=theintercept.com|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure at the CIA, his analytical assignments included monitoring the breakup of the former [[Soviet Union]]; providing military assessments to policy makers on [[Iraq]]i and [[Iran]]ian conventional forces and coordinating the CIA's military targeting support to [[NATO]] during [[Operation Deliberate Force]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]] in 1995.\n\nEddington resigned in 1996 after working on the book ''Gassed in the Gulf: The Inside Story of the Pentagon-CIA Cover-up of Gulf War Syndrome'', in which he presented the claim of substantial evidence that American soldiers were exposed to chemical agents during the Persian Gulf War in 1991.\n\nHis CIA memoir, ''Long Strange Journey'', was published in 2011. In a 2011 interview with the Washington Post, Eddington accused the CIA of still withholding 1.5 million documents relevant to the Desert Storm malady known as [[gulf war syndrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/spy-talk/2011/02/ex-cia_analyst_patrcik_eddingt.html|title=SpyTalk - Ex-CIA analyst Patrick Eddington accuses agency of \u2018sitting on\u2019 Gulf War illness documents|work=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nEddington's opinion pieces have appeared in numerous of publications, including the ''[[Washington Post]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[Washington Times]]'', ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'', and the ''[[Army Times]]''. Eddington is a frequent commentator on national security issues for the [[Fox News Channel]], [[MSNBC]], [[SKY News]], [[CNN]], and other domestic and international television networks.\n\n== Books ==\n* ''Gassed in the Gulf: The Inside Story of the Pentagon-CIA Cover-up of Gulf War Syndrome'', August 1997, Insignia Publishing Company\n* ''Long Strange Journey: An Intelligence Memoir'', 2011\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.patrickeddington.com Eddington home page]\n*{{C-SPAN|Patrick Eddington}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eddington, Patrick G.}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People of the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Gulf War syndrome]]\n[[Category:American whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1988-1996 \u2192 1988\u20131996", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_G._Eddington"}
{"title_page": "Deesha Dyer", "text_new": "{{short description|American public servant|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Deesha Dyer\n|office      = 30th [[White House Social Secretary]]\n|image       = File:P021114CK-1183.jpg\n|caption     = Deesha Dyer in the Green Room of the White House after the completion of the France State Dinner.\n|term_start  = April 16, 2015\n|term_end    = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor = [[Jeremy Bernard]]\n|president   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|successor   = [[Anna Cristina Niceta Lloyd]]\n|office1     = Deputy [[White House Social Secretary]]\n|term_start1 = 2013\n|term_end1   = April 16, 2015\n|predecessor1= \n|successor1  = \n|president1  = [[Barack Obama]]\n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1978|1|15}}\n|birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]],<br>[[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|alma_mater  = [[Community College of Philadelphia|Community College of<br>Philadelphia]]<br>[[Milton Hershey School]]\n}}\n\n'''Deesha Dyer''' (born 1978) is an American public servant who served as the [[White House Social Secretary]] for [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] from 2015 to 2017. Dyer also served as Deputy to the previous Social Secretary, [[Jeremy Bernard]].  Her White House career began as an intern in the [[White House Office of Scheduling and Advance|Office of Scheduling and Advance]] in Fall 2009. She was the Obama administration's fourth social secretary and the second of [[African-American]] descent. Before working at the White House she worked as the executive assistant at the [[Pennsylvania Real Estate Investment Trust]] and a freelance writer at the [[Philadelphia Citypaper]].  She is from [[Philadelphia, PA|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.]]<ref>[http://www.linkedin.com/profile/view?id=387604839&authType=NAME_SEARCH&authToken=PhaK&locale=en_US&trk=tyah&trkInfo=clickedVertical%3Amynetwork%2Cidx%3A1-1-1%2CtarId%3A1434329983775%2Ctas%3ADeesha%20Dyer] {{dead link|date=August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2015-04-18/news/61257685_1_jeremy-bernard-white-house-first-lady|title=Archives - Philly.com|website=articles.philly.com|accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/04/16/white-house-announces-deesha-dyer-social-secretary|title=White House Announces Deesha Dyer as Social Secretary|date=16 April 2015|website=Whitehouse.gov|accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nDyer won a 2017 [[NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Award]] for the [[BET]] special ''Love & Happiness: An Obama Celebration''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/827168/naacp-image-awards-2017-winners-the-complete-list|title=NAACP Image Awards 2017 Winners: The Complete List|work=E! Online|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref> She volunteers her time as the Executive Director of Philadelphia-based teen girl travel group, beGirl.world. In 2017, she was signed as a speaker to Outspoken Agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.outspokenagency.com/deesha-dyer/|title=Deesha Dyer|website=outspoken|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> In 2018, she contributed a chapter to ''[https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/572629/west-wingers-by-edited-by-gautam-raghavan/ West Wingers: Stories from the Dream Chasers, Change Makers, and Hope Creators Inside the Obama White House]'' recounting her experiences in the Obama White House.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/572629/west-wingers-by-edited-by-gautam-raghavan/|title=West Wingers {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDyer has been featured in national media outlets including ''TIME,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3825805/deesha-dyer-white-house-social-secretary/|title=Meet the White House's New Social Secretary|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> ''The New York Times, Elle,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/a14557984/deesha-dyer-interview/|title=How I Went from a 31-Year-Old White House Intern To Barack Obama\u2019s Social Secretary|date=2018-01-10|work=ELLE|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref> ''Marie Claire,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/career-advice/news/a15230/white-house-social-secretary-deesha-dyer/|title=Inside the Life of New White House Social Secretary Deesha Dyer|date=2015-07-27|work=Marie Claire|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref> ''Essence,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.essence.com/2015/04/16/deesha-dyer-named-new-white-house-social-secretary|title=Deesha Dyer Named New White House Social Secretary|work=Essence.com|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en}}</ref> ''Vogue, Refinery29,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.refinery29.com/2015/04/85767/deesha-dyer-new-white-house-social-secretary-announced|title=Meet The White House's New Chief Party Planner|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en}}</ref> ''Forbes, The Root,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theroot.com/and-the-new-white-house-social-secretary-is-deesha-1790859481|title=And the New White House Social Secretary Is ... Deesha Dyer|last=Eromosele|first=Diana Ozemebhoya|work=The Root|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref> and ''Washington Post.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/deesha-dyer-how-a-hip-hop-lover-from-philly-became-social-secretary/2015/05/07/97f93098-ef48-11e4-8abc-d6aa3bad79dd_story.html|title=How Deesha Dyer, a hip-hop lover from Philly, became social secretary|last=Thompson|first=Krissah|date=2015-05-07|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Bernard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Social Secretary]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Anna Cristina Niceta Lloyd]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dyer, Deesha}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Community College of Philadelphia alumni]]\n[[Category:Milton Hershey School alumni]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Philadelphia]]\n\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American public servant|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Deesha Dyer\n|office      = 30th [[White House Social Secretary]]\n|image       = File:P021114CK-1183.jpg\n|caption     = Deesha Dyer in the Green Room of the White House after the completion of the France State Dinner.\n|term_start  = April 16, 2015\n|term_end    = January 20, 2017\n|predecessor = [[Jeremy Bernard]]\n|president   = [[Barack Obama]]\n|successor   = [[Anna Cristina Niceta Lloyd]]\n|office1     = Deputy [[White House Social Secretary]]\n|term_start1 = 2013\n|term_end1   = April 16, 2015\n|predecessor1= \n|successor1  = \n|president1  = [[Barack Obama]]\n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1978|1|15}}\n|birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]],<br>[[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|alma_mater  = [[Community College of Philadelphia|Community College of<br>Philadelphia]]<br>[[Milton Hershey School]]\n}}\n\n'''Deesha Dyer''' (born 1978) is an American public servant who served as the [[White House Social Secretary]] for [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] from 2015 to 2017. Dyer also served as Deputy to the previous Social Secretary, [[Jeremy Bernard]].  Her White House career began as an intern in the [[White House Office of Scheduling and Advance|Office of Scheduling and Advance]] in Fall 2009. She was the Obama administration's fourth social secretary and the second of [[African-American]] descent. Before working at the White House she worked as the executive assistant at the [[Pennsylvania Real Estate Investment Trust]] and a freelance writer at the [[Philadelphia Citypaper]].  She is from [[Philadelphia, PA|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.]]<ref>[http://www.linkedin.com/profile/view?id=387604839&authType=NAME_SEARCH&authToken=PhaK&locale=en_US&trk=tyah&trkInfo=clickedVertical%3Amynetwork%2Cidx%3A1-1-1%2CtarId%3A1434329983775%2Ctas%3ADeesha%20Dyer] {{dead link|date=August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2015-04-18/news/61257685_1_jeremy-bernard-white-house-first-lady|title=Archives - Philly.com|website=articles.philly.com|accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/04/16/white-house-announces-deesha-dyer-social-secretary|title=White House Announces Deesha Dyer as Social Secretary|date=16 April 2015|website=Whitehouse.gov|accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nDyer won a 2017 [[NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Award]] for the [[BET]] special ''Love & Happiness: An Obama Celebration''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/827168/naacp-image-awards-2017-winners-the-complete-list|title=NAACP Image Awards 2017 Winners: The Complete List|work=E! Online|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref> She volunteers her time as the Executive Director of Philadelphia based teen girl travel group, beGirl.world. In 2017, she was signed as a speaker to Outspoken Agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.outspokenagency.com/deesha-dyer/|title=Deesha Dyer|website=outspoken|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> In 2018, she contributed a chapter to ''[https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/572629/west-wingers-by-edited-by-gautam-raghavan/ West Wingers: Stories from the Dream Chasers, Change Makers, and Hope Creators Inside the Obama White House]'' recounting her experiences in the Obama White House.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/572629/west-wingers-by-edited-by-gautam-raghavan/|title=West Wingers {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDyer has been featured in national media outlets including ''TIME,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3825805/deesha-dyer-white-house-social-secretary/|title=Meet the White House's New Social Secretary|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> ''The New York Times, Elle,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/a14557984/deesha-dyer-interview/|title=How I Went from a 31-Year-Old White House Intern To Barack Obama\u2019s Social Secretary|date=2018-01-10|work=ELLE|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref> ''Marie Claire,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/career-advice/news/a15230/white-house-social-secretary-deesha-dyer/|title=Inside the Life of New White House Social Secretary Deesha Dyer|date=2015-07-27|work=Marie Claire|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref> ''Essence,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.essence.com/2015/04/16/deesha-dyer-named-new-white-house-social-secretary|title=Deesha Dyer Named New White House Social Secretary|work=Essence.com|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en}}</ref> ''Vogue, Refinery29,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.refinery29.com/2015/04/85767/deesha-dyer-new-white-house-social-secretary-announced|title=Meet The White House's New Chief Party Planner|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en}}</ref> ''Forbes, The Root,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theroot.com/and-the-new-white-house-social-secretary-is-deesha-1790859481|title=And the New White House Social Secretary Is ... Deesha Dyer|last=Eromosele|first=Diana Ozemebhoya|work=The Root|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref> and ''Washington Post.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/deesha-dyer-how-a-hip-hop-lover-from-philly-became-social-secretary/2015/05/07/97f93098-ef48-11e4-8abc-d6aa3bad79dd_story.html|title=How Deesha Dyer, a hip-hop lover from Philly, became social secretary|last=Thompson|first=Krissah|date=2015-05-07|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Bernard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Social Secretary]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Anna Cristina Niceta Lloyd]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dyer, Deesha}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Community College of Philadelphia alumni]]\n[[Category:Milton Hershey School alumni]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Philadelphia]]\n\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: Philadelphia based \u2192 Philadelphia-based", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deesha_Dyer"}
{"title_page": "George Diller", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name = George H. Diller\n|image = George Diller April 2017.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|caption = Diller in April 2017\n|birth_date =\n|birth_place =Sarasota, Florida\n|home_town =Titusville, Florida\n|death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place =\n|other_names =\n|known_for = launch commentary\n|occupation = retired public affairs officer at Kennedy Space Center, [[NASA]]\n|nationality = US\n|employer = NASA\n|spouse =\n}}\n'''George Diller''' is a retired [[public relations]] specialist who worked in the [[NASA]] Public Affairs Office (PAO) at the [[Kennedy Space Center]]. He provided public announcements and commentary before and during launches from the Kennedy Space Center, including the [[space shuttle]] and unmanned spacecraft such as the [[Mars rover]]s [[Spirit rover|Spirit]] and [[Opportunity rover|Opportunity]], and was known as \"The Voice of Kennedy Space Center\".  Diller provided launch commentary from the launch of [[STS-27]] through [[STS-135]] the final launch of the program.<ref name=\"iya365\">{{cite web|url=https://cosmoquest.org/x/365daysofastronomy/2011/10/19/october-19th/|title=An interview with George Diller|last=Rice|first=Tony|date=October 19, 2011|work=[[365 Days of Astronomy]] Podcast|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref>   He is also known for his \"liftoff line\" he gave as the shuttle and other vehicles lifted off the pad.<ref name=firstcoast /> \n\nIn addition to shuttle missions, Diller served as commentator during the roll-out, launch delays, and successful launch of [[Ares I-X]] in October 2009 as well as planetary missions such as [[Juno (spacecraft)|Juno]], [[GRAIL]], [[Mars Science Laboratory]], and [[MAVEN]].  Diller lists among his favorite moments, the launch of the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] aboard [[STS-31]], [[Magellan (spacecraft)|Magellan]] and [[Galileo (spacecraft)|Galileo]] probes which he had much involvement in, and his first shuttle launch commentary for the [[STS-27]] mission.<ref name=firstcoast>{{cite news|title=Behind The Scenes At NASA: Voice of the Countdown |url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/article/209989/3/Behind-The-Scenes-At-NASA-Voice-of-the-Countdown |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130124061814/http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/article/209989/3/Behind-The-Scenes-At-NASA-Voice-of-the-Countdown |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-24 |newspaper=First Coast News }}</ref>\n\nDiller's final launch commentary was for the [[Cygnus CRS OA-7]] mission on April 18, 2017. After the launch, Diller interviewed KSC Director and former astronaut [[Robert D. Cabana|Bob Cabana]] for the [[NASA TV]] feed, who pointed out that the launch was Diller's last.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/orbital/2017/04/18/longtime-nasa-launch-commentator-george-diller-to-step-away-from-the-console/|title=Longtime NASA Launch Commentator George Diller to Step Away from the Console|last=Heiney|first=Anna|date=18 April 2017|website=blogs.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA |access-date=19 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nDiller appeared as himself in mission control scenes in the comedy action made-for-television movie [[Sharknado 3: Oh Hell No!|Sharknado 3]].\n\n==Background==\nDiller is a native Floridian, having grown up in [[Sarasota, Florida|Sarasota]] and Clearwater. He graduated from the University of South Florida, Tampa campus first in 1972 and then later in 1977. He has lived in [[Titusville, Florida|Titusville]] since October 1978. He worked for 11 years in [[radio broadcasting]] at stations in [[Clearwater, Florida|Clearwater]], [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] and [[Orlando, Florida]], and had among his responsibilities covering the Kennedy Space Center as a reporter.<ref>[http://www.nasa.gov/centers/kennedy/about/biographies/diller.html NASA - George H. Diller, NASA Public Affairs Information Specialist]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jack King (NASA)|Jack King]]\n\n==References==\n{{Include-NASA}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.nasa.gov/centers/kennedy/about/biographies/diller.html}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oP1pVyAR904 montage of George Diller space shuttle launch commentary]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diller, George}}\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Sarasota, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Clearwater, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Titusville, Florida]]\n\n\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name = George H. Diller\n|image = George Diller April 2017.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|caption = Diller in April 2017\n|birth_date =\n|birth_place =Sarasota, Florida\n|home_town =Titusville, Florida\n|death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place =\n|other_names =\n|known_for = launch commentary\n|occupation = retired public affairs officer at Kennedy Space Center, [[NASA]]\n|nationality = US\n|employer = NASA\n|spouse =\n}}\n'''George Diller''' is a retired [[public relations]] specialist who worked in the [[NASA]] Public Affairs Office (PAO) at the [[Kennedy Space Center]]. He provided public announcements and commentary before and during launches from the Kennedy Space Center, including the [[space shuttle]] and unmanned spacecraft such as the [[Mars rover]]s [[Spirit rover|Spirit]] and [[Opportunity rover|Opportunity]], and was known as \"The Voice of Kennedy Space Center\".  Diller provided launch commentary from the launch of [[STS-27]] through [[STS-135]] the final launch of the program.<ref name=\"iya365\">{{cite web|url=https://cosmoquest.org/x/365daysofastronomy/2011/10/19/october-19th/|title=An interview with George Diller|last=Rice|first=Tony|date=October 19, 2011|work=[[365 Days of Astronomy]] Podcast|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=19 October 2011}}</ref>   He is also known for his \"liftoff line\" he gave as the shuttle and other vehicles lifted off the pad.<ref name=firstcoast /> \n\nIn addition to shuttle missions, Diller served as commentator during the roll-out, launch delays, and successful launch of [[Ares I-X]] in October 2009 as well as planetary missions such as [[Juno (spacecraft)|Juno]], [[GRAIL]], [[Mars Science Laboratory]], and [[MAVEN]].  Diller lists among his favorite moments, the launch of the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] aboard [[STS-31]], [[Magellan (spacecraft)|Magellan]] and [[Galileo (spacecraft)|Galileo]] probes which he had much involvement in, and his first shuttle launch commentary for the [[STS-27]] mission.<ref name=firstcoast>{{cite news|title=Behind The Scenes At NASA: Voice of the Countdown |url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/article/209989/3/Behind-The-Scenes-At-NASA-Voice-of-the-Countdown |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130124061814/http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/article/209989/3/Behind-The-Scenes-At-NASA-Voice-of-the-Countdown |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-24 |newspaper=First Coast News }}</ref>\n\nDiller's final launch commentary was for the [[Cygnus CRS OA-7]] mission on April 18, 2017. After the launch, Diller interviewed KSC Director and former astronaut [[Robert D. Cabana|Bob Cabana]] for the [[NASA TV]] feed, who pointed out that the launch was Diller's last.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/orbital/2017/04/18/longtime-nasa-launch-commentator-george-diller-to-step-away-from-the-console/|title=Longtime NASA Launch Commentator George Diller to Step Away from the Console|last=Heiney|first=Anna|date=18 April 2017|website=blogs.nasa.gov|publisher=NASA |access-date=19 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nDiller appeared as himself in mission control scenes in the comedy action made for television movie [[Sharknado 3: Oh Hell No!|Sharknado 3]].\n\n==Background==\nDiller is a native Floridian, having grown up in [[Sarasota, Florida|Sarasota]] and Clearwater. He graduated from the University of South Florida, Tampa campus first in 1972 and then later in 1977. He has lived in [[Titusville, Florida|Titusville]] since October 1978. He worked for 11 years in [[radio broadcasting]] at stations in [[Clearwater, Florida|Clearwater]], [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] and [[Orlando, Florida]], and had among his responsibilities covering the Kennedy Space Center as a reporter.<ref>[http://www.nasa.gov/centers/kennedy/about/biographies/diller.html NASA - George H. Diller, NASA Public Affairs Information Specialist]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jack King (NASA)|Jack King]]\n\n==References==\n{{Include-NASA}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.nasa.gov/centers/kennedy/about/biographies/diller.html}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oP1pVyAR904 montage of George Diller space shuttle launch commentary]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diller, George}}\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Sarasota, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Clearwater, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Titusville, Florida]]\n\n\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: made for television movie \u2192 made-for-television movie", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Diller"}
{"title_page": "Mike Donehey", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Michael Donehey\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| image_size      = \n| birth_name      = Michael Morgan Donehey \n| background      = solo_singer\n| born            = September 30\n| birth_place     = [[Omaha, Nebraska]], United States\n| instrument      = Vocals, [[acoustic guitar]]\n| genre           = [[Christian rock]], [[Contemporary Christian music|CCM]]\n| occupation      = [[Musician]]\n| years_active    = 2000-present\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = [[Tenth Avenue North]] \n| website         = \n}}\n'''Michael Morgan \"Mike\" Donehey''' (born September 30, 1981) is an American singer, songwriter, and guitarist primarily known for his work in the [[Christian rock]] band [[Tenth Avenue North]].\n\n== Early life ==\nDonehey was born to Dan and Sharon Donehey in [[Omaha, Nebraska]] in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Donehey Biography|url=http://www.tenthavenuenation.com/band/biographies/mike/|website=Tenth Avenue Nation|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> He graduated from Fredericksburg Christian School in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]] in 1999. He attended FCS from [[kindergarten]] through graduation and played [[varsity team|varsity]]<!--Between kindergarten and high school?--> [[soccer]].<ref>https://fredericksburgchristian.com/engage/2018/05/24/guitars-babies-and-broken-bones-the-musical-journey-of-tenth-avenue-north-frontman-mike-donehey-99/</ref> Donehey was involved in a near-fatal, single-car accident on Mine Road in [[Spotsylvania County]] during his senior year of high school. He broke his back in two places, broke his skull, and had an ear ripped off. He was told he would never walk again. He picked up a guitar during his days in the hospital and began to write music.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Somers|first1=Liz|title=Tenth Avenue North's Donehey Finds Beauty|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/highernote/tag/mike-donehey/|website=The Denver Post|publisher=The Denver Post}}</ref> He recovered and moved to Florida to attend [[Palm Beach Atlantic University]] where Tenth Avenue North was formed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Lindsey|title=Christian College Alums: Mike Donehey from Tenth Avenue North|url=http://thesoundopinion.com/2010/08/08/christian-college-alums-part-1-mike-donehey-from-tenth-avenue-north/|website=The Sound Opinion|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Musical and Written Work ==\nDonehey has been with Tenth Avenue North since 2000 and continues to write and perform on tour and in the studio. He also regularly contributes to fellow Christian musicians' work with performances on recent records from [[Hawk Nelson]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Through The Fire (feat. Mike Donehey)|url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/lyrics/new/track.asp?track_id=16738|website=Jesus Freak Hideout|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> [[Lecrae]], and [[Jars of Clay]], among others. On August 6, 2019, Donehey published his first book entitled ''Finding God's Life for My Will: His Presence is the Plan''. The book was an [[Evangelical Christian Publishers Association|ECPA]] Bestseller.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waterbrookmultnomah.com/books/586107/finding-gods-life-for-my-will-by-mike-donehey/|title=Finding God's Life for My Will by Mike Donehey|website=WaterBrook & Multnomah|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donehey, Mike}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American performers of Christian music]]\n[[Category:Palm Beach Atlantic University alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Nebraska]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Michael Donehey\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| image_size      = \n| birth_name      = Michael Morgan Donehey \n| background      = solo_singer\n| born            = September 30\n| birth_place     = [[Omaha, Nebraska]], United States\n| instrument      = Vocals, [[acoustic guitar]]\n| genre           = [[Christian rock]], [[Contemporary Christian music|CCM]]\n| occupation      = [[Musician]]\n| years_active    = 2000-present\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = [[Tenth Avenue North]] \n| website         = \n}}\n'''Michael Morgan \"Mike\" Donehey''' (born September 30, 1981) is an American singer, songwriter, and guitarist primarily known for his work in the [[Christian rock]] band [[Tenth Avenue North]].\n\n== Early life ==\nDonehey was born to Dan and Sharon Donehey in [[Omaha, Nebraska]] in [[1981]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Donehey Biography|url=http://www.tenthavenuenation.com/band/biographies/mike/|website=Tenth Avenue Nation|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> He graduated from Fredericksburg Christian School in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]] in 1999. He attended FCS from [[kindergarten]] through graduation and played [[varsity team|varsity]]<!--Between kindergarten and high school?--> [[soccer]].<ref>https://fredericksburgchristian.com/engage/2018/05/24/guitars-babies-and-broken-bones-the-musical-journey-of-tenth-avenue-north-frontman-mike-donehey-99/</ref> Donehey was involved in a near-fatal, single-car accident on Mine Road in [[Spotsylvania County]] during his senior year of high school. He broke his back in two places, broke his skull, and had an ear ripped off. He was told he would never walk again. He picked up a guitar during his days in the hospital and began to write music.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Somers|first1=Liz|title=Tenth Avenue North's Donehey Finds Beauty|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/highernote/tag/mike-donehey/|website=The Denver Post|publisher=The Denver Post}}</ref> He recovered and moved to Florida to attend [[Palm Beach Atlantic University]] where Tenth Avenue North was formed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Lindsey|title=Christian College Alums: Mike Donehey from Tenth Avenue North|url=http://thesoundopinion.com/2010/08/08/christian-college-alums-part-1-mike-donehey-from-tenth-avenue-north/|website=The Sound Opinion|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> \n\n== Musical and Written Work ==\nDonehey has been with Tenth Avenue North since 2000 and continues to write and perform on tour and in the studio. He also regularly contributes to fellow Christian musicians' work with performances on recent records from [[Hawk Nelson]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Through The Fire (feat. Mike Donehey)|url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/lyrics/new/track.asp?track_id=16738|website=Jesus Freak Hideout|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> [[Lecrae]], and [[Jars of Clay]], among others. On August 6, 2019, Donehey published his first book entitled ''Finding God's Life for My Will: His Presence is the Plan''. The book was an [[Evangelical Christian Publishers Association|ECPA]] Bestseller.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://waterbrookmultnomah.com/books/586107/finding-gods-life-for-my-will-by-mike-donehey/|title=Finding God's Life for My Will by Mike Donehey|website=WaterBrook & Multnomah|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donehey, Mike}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American performers of Christian music]]\n[[Category:Palm Beach Atlantic University alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Nebraska]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:clean up, replaced:1981\u2192 1981", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Donehey"}
{"title_page": "Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig\n| image = \n| fullname = Sport-Club Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig\n| nickname = \n| founded = 11 November 1893\n| ground = Exerzierplatz (until 1899) <br> Sportplatz (from 1900)\n| capacity = \n| chairman = \n| manager = \n| league = \n| position = \n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = \n| pattern_ra2 = |\n| dissolved = 2 November 1900\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n'''Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig''' was a [[Football in Germany|German association football club]] from the city of [[Leipzig]], [[Saxony]], which co-existed alongside an athletics and cycling team of the name ''Sportbr\u00fcder''.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.speedskatingnews.info/en/results/?eventID=1864&gender=m|title=Competition: Wettlaufen des Clubs \"Sportbr\u00fcder\"|last=|first=|date=|website=Speed Skating News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> It was one of the older teams in Leipzig's football history, as it was the fourth to be established in the city on 11 November 1893 \u2014 the same year as [[Leipzig BC 1893]] and [[\u201cFC Lipsia 1893 Leipzig|\u201cFC Lipsia 1893]], and one year after [[VfK S\u00fcdwest Leipzig]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://betsnn.com/the-emblems-of-the-bundesliga-rb-leipzig/|title=Evolution of the emblems of the Bundesliga. \u201cRB Leipzig\u201d|last=Malone|first=David|date=2019|website=Betsnnn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Hesse-Lichtenberger|first=Ulrich|title=Tor!: The Story of German Football|publisher=WSC Books Limited|year=2003|isbn=978-0954013455|location=London|pages=24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fussball-historie.de/Vereinsgruendungen/Gruendungen1895.html|title=Vereinsgr\u00fcndungen bis 1895|last=|first=|date=|website=fussball-historie.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>. The team was initially set up by young athletes from the [[ATV Leipzig 1845]] athletics association and managed by them until becoming independent on May 26 1896, spurred on by the loss of the team to Leizpig BC 1893 and the demanding training schedule being enforced by the athletics association. This was a common occurrence at the turn of the century, with other teams such as [[FC Bayern Munich]] also choosing to part ways with their men's gymnastics club.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe team competed in the [[Verband Leipziger Ballspiel-Vereine]] (Federation of Leipzig Ballgame Clubs), the third established football league in Germany, for two seasons. In both seasons they placed bottom of the table and are considered to have dissolved from 2 November 1900 following the departure of original members after a team merger. 1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig claim to be their successors.\n\n==History==\nFounded in November 1893 by Johannes Kirmse and [[Albert R\u00f6\u00dfler]] as ''Sport Club Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig'' it was one of Germany's earliest football clubs and a [[Founding Clubs of the DFB|founding member]] of the [[German Football Association]] (Deutscher Fussball Bund or German Football Association) in 1900<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://initiative1903.com/fussballhistorie/clubgruendungen/|title=Clubgr\u00fcndungen|last=|first=|date=|website=Initiative 1903 e.V.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.austria-archiv.at/mannschaft.php?mode=heim&Mannschaft_ID=181|title=Leipzig, VfB|last=|first=|date=15 June 2006|website=Austria-Archiv.at|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>. Initially the squad almost exclusively consisted of students under 20 years old from a local [[Realschule]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Sachse|first=Horst|title=Fussball in und um Leipzig: von den Anf\u00e4ngen bis 1945|publisher=Leipziger Universit\u00e4tsverlag|year=2000|isbn=393456514X|location=|pages=25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Rackwitz|first=Ingolf|title=Zentralstadion Leipzig: vom Stadion der Hunderttausend zum Fussballtempel|publisher=Das Neue Berlin|year=2006|isbn=978-3360012807|location=|pages=15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Dieter Baroth|first=Hans|title=Als der Fussball laufen lernte: Tore, Triumphe, Tollheiten|publisher=Klartext|year=1992|isbn=978-3884744680|location=|pages=70}}</ref> The team also became a part of the Verband Leipziger Ballspiel Vereine on 30 March 1987, being the first team accepted into the federation after the initial founding members.<ref name=\":2\" /> Despite winning the last game of the 1899/1900 season against [[FC Wacker Leipzig]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.leipziger-fussballverband.de/cms2/index.php?page=152|title=1896 - 1899|last=|first=|date=10 February 2009|website=Leipziger Fussballverband|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leipziger-fussballverband.de/cms2/index.php?page=153|title=1900 - 1909|last=|first=|date=21 November 2010|website=Leipziger Fu\u00dfballverband|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>, they still placed at the bottom of the table for the second year in a row. All four founding members of this federation and Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig initially shared the [[Parade ground|Exerzierplatz]], formerly a military parade ground, in [[Rosenthal]]. Following the closure of the ground in 1899<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.speedskatingnews.info/en/data/rink/LPS/|title=Rink Card Of: Exerzierplatz Leipzig|last=|first=|date=|website=Speed Skating News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> the Sportplatz was instead used by the teams as a their playing ground. The other four teams using the ground were:\n\n* Leipziger Ballspiel-Club\n* FC Wacker Leipzig\n* VfB Leipzig\n* Abteilung Bewegungsspiele der Leipziger Finkenschaft.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n[[File:Leipzig - B\u00fcttnerstra\u00dfe - 10 01 ies oG.jpg|alt=German plaque outside Zum Marriengarten, which translates into English as \"Here, in the former 'Zum Marriengarten' restaurant, the German Football Association was founded on the 28 January 1900.\" Underneath this text is a inscription noting that the German Football Association and city of Leipzig put up this plaque on the 100th anniversary in the year 2000.|left|thumb|Plaque outside ''Zum Marriengarten'' which commemorates the founding of the German Football Association.|236x236px]]\nFollowing a meeting at the restaurant ''Zum Mariengarten,'' the same location where the German Football Association was founded, Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig merged with ''[[VfB Leipzig]]'' in 1898 to form ''VfB Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig''<ref name=\":0\" /> until the name was changed to the older VfB Leipzig on 2 November 1900.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dsc-museum.de/gegner/vfb-leipzig/|title=Verein f\u00fcr Bewegungsspiele Leipzig|last=|first=|date=|website=DSC Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/team/soccer/vfb-leipzig/561/|title=VfB Leipzig - Team Info|last=|first=|date=|website=Global Sports Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> This decision was encouraged by Thomas Sch\u00f6ffler<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schr\u00f6ter|first=Detlev|title=Camillo Ugi: Weltklassefu\u00dfballer|publisher=Engelsdorfer Verlag|year=2018|isbn=978-3961454006|location=|pages=10}}</ref> and proved to be of both personal and financial benefit for the teams.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe athletic department of ''Sportbr\u00fcder'' organized the country's first [[marathon]] on 5 September 1897 from [[Paunsdorf]] to [[Bennewitz]] and back, for which eighteen participants signed up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.speedskatingnews.info/en/results/?eventID=1864&gender=m|title=Competition: Wettlaufen des Clubs \"Sportbr\u00fcder\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Duwe|first=Klaus|title=42 mal 42: Marathon-Erlebnisse von Antalya bis Zermatt|publisher=Copress Sport|year=2008|isbn=978-3767910102|location=Germany|pages=77}}</ref> At 6 am the race began at Neuen Gasthof in Paunsdorf with Theodor Sch\u00f6ffler, a referee for VfB Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig and future founder of the German Football Association<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://germanroadraces.de/?p=58777|title=Der Leipzig Marathon \u2013 Stationen vom Elite- zum Volkslauf \u2013 die Geschichte des Laufes in 3 Folgen|last=|first=|date=9 December 2007|website=German Road Races|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>, being the first out of thirteen participants to cross the finish line at a time of 3:35:51. According to media reports, the race was received well by spectators.<ref name=\":5\" /> Another race took place the following year, but this time organised by the newly founded ''Deutschen Sportbeh\u00f6rde f\u00fcr Athletik (German Sports Authority for Athletics)''.<ref>\"[https://www.stadtgeschichtliches-museum-leipzig.de/fileadmin/user_upload/Konzept_Sportroute_final_Stand30072019.pdf Sportroute Leipzig\"] ''Stadtgeschichtliches Museum Leipzig'' Retrieved 9 April 2020.</ref> The athletic's division also had a prominent [[ice skating]] team.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nThe first national marathon championship in Germany was held in 1925 with the course beginning in [[Halle, Saxony-Anhalt|Halle]] and ending in [[Leipzig]] to commemorate the Sportbr\u00fcder athletics department's contribution to, and establishment of, the sport.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gottert|first=Frank|title=Marathon-Mekka Leipzig|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=9}}</ref> \n\n== Successors ==\nIt has sometimes been claimed that Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig completely separated from VfB Leipzig in 1900 and faded into obscurity<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundsinfocus.com/TT1011206.htm|title=Lokomotive Leipzig|last=|first=|date=21 March 2011|website=Football Grounds in Focus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>, but this belief is either due to a  possible misinterpretation of the German team ''Umbenennung'' (''renaming'') with reference to the change of VfB Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig to VfB Leizpig, or due to the departure of many, but not all, of the original Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig members.<ref name=\":4\" /> Under the name <nowiki>''VfB Leipzig''</nowiki> they enjoyed considerable success as one of the 86 founding clubs of the [[German Football Association]] and were the winners of the [[1903 German football championship|1903 German football championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wasistwas.de/details-sport-freizeit/wann-wurde-der-dfb-gegruendet-6793.html|title=Wann wurde der DFB gegr\u00fcndet?|last=|first=|date=|website=Was ist Was|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> At the founding of the German Football Association, under the name VfB Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig, they were represented by the chairman of the Federation of Leipzig Ballgame Teams [[Johannes Kirmse]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Spiel und Sport|date=3 February 1900|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|issue=444|edition=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Insolvency]] of VfB Leipzig at the end of 2004, [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]] claims to be the successor of the original Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig and considers the team to be their \"founding fathers\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lok-leipzig.com/verein/geschichte/1893-1914-pionierarbeit-unter-der-pickelhaube/|title=Pionierarbeit Unter Der Pickelhaube (1893-1914)|last=|first=|date=|website=1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>, since they are seeking to purchase the defunct club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fussball.de/newsdetail/lok-leipzig-fusion-mit-vfb-ist-naeher-gerueckt/-/article-id/196244#!/|title=Lok Leipzig: Fusion mit VfB ist n\u00e4her ger\u00fcckt|last=|first=|date=28 November 2018|website=Fussball.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Should the deal go ahead, this would make them the nominal descendants of the team, but fans still consider the founding date of 1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig to be 1966 instead of 1893.\n== Results ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+As ''VfB'' ''Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig''\n!Season\n!Competition\n!Result\n|-\n|1899/1900\n|Federation of Leipzig Ballgame Teams Championship\n|4th (last)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asc-neuenheim.de/ergebnisse/saison_1899-00/leipzig_1899.htm|title=Verband Leipziger Ballspiel Vereine 1899/00|last=|first=|date=|website=asc-neuenheim.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|1898/1899\n|Federation of Leipzig Ballgame Teams Championship\n|4th (last)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asc-neuenheim.de/ergebnisse/saison_1898-99/leipzig_1898.htm|title=Verband Leipziger Ballspiel Vereine 1898/99|last=|first=|date=|website=asc-neuenheim.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leipzig, Sportbruder}}\n[[Category:Football clubs in Germany]]\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in Germany]]\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in Saxony]]\n[[Category:Sport in Leipzig|Sportbruder]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1893]]\n[[Category:1893 establishments in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig\n| image = \n| fullname = Sport-Club Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig\n| nickname = \n| founded = 11 November 1893\n| ground = Exerzierplatz (until 1899) <br> Sportplatz (from 1900)\n| capacity = \n| chairman = \n| manager = \n| league = \n| position = \n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = \n| pattern_ra2 = |\n| dissolved = 2 November 1900\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n'''Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig''' was a [[Football in Germany|German association football club]] from the city of [[Leipzig]], [[Saxony]], which co-existed alongside an athletics and cycling team of the name ''Sportbr\u00fcder''.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.speedskatingnews.info/en/results/?eventID=1864&gender=m|title=Competition: Wettlaufen des Clubs \"Sportbr\u00fcder\"|last=|first=|date=|website=Speed Skating News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> It was one of the older teams in Leipzig's football history, as it was the fourth to be established in the city on 11 November 1893 \u2014 the same year as [[Leipzig BC 1893]] and [[\u201cFC Lipsia 1893 Leipzig|\u201cFC Lipsia 1893]], and one year after [[VfK S\u00fcdwest Leipzig]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://betsnn.com/the-emblems-of-the-bundesliga-rb-leipzig/|title=Evolution of the emblems of the Bundesliga. \u201cRB Leipzig\u201d|last=Malone|first=David|date=2019|website=Betsnnn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Hesse-Lichtenberger|first=Ulrich|title=Tor!: The Story of German Football|publisher=WSC Books Limited|year=2003|isbn=978-0954013455|location=London|pages=24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fussball-historie.de/Vereinsgruendungen/Gruendungen1895.html|title=Vereinsgr\u00fcndungen bis 1895|last=|first=|date=|website=fussball-historie.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>. The team was initially set up by young athletes from the [[ATV Leipzig 1845]] athletics association and managed by them until becoming independent on May 26 1896, spurred on by the loss of the team to Leizpig BC 1893 and the demanding training schedule being enforced by the athletics association. This was a common occurrence at the turn of the century, with other teams such as [[FC Bayern Munich]] also choosing to part ways with their men's gymnastics club.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe team competed in the [[Verband Leipziger Ballspiel-Vereine]] (Federation of Leipzig Ballgame Clubs), the third established football league in Germany, for two seasons. In both seasons they placed bottom of the table and are considered to have dissolved from 2 November 1900, following the departure of original members following a team merger. 1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig claim to be their successors.\n\n==History==\nFounded in November 1893 by Johannes Kirmse and [[Albert R\u00f6\u00dfler]] as ''Sport Club Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig'' it was one of Germany's earliest football clubs and a [[Founding Clubs of the DFB|founding member]] of the [[German Football Association]] (Deutscher Fussball Bund or German Football Association) in 1900<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://initiative1903.com/fussballhistorie/clubgruendungen/|title=Clubgr\u00fcndungen|last=|first=|date=|website=Initiative 1903 e.V.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.austria-archiv.at/mannschaft.php?mode=heim&Mannschaft_ID=181|title=Leipzig, VfB|last=|first=|date=15 June 2006|website=Austria-Archiv.at|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>. Initially the squad almost exclusively consisted of students under 20 years old from a local [[Realschule]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Sachse|first=Horst|title=Fussball in und um Leipzig: von den Anf\u00e4ngen bis 1945|publisher=Leipziger Universit\u00e4tsverlag|year=2000|isbn=393456514X|location=|pages=25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Rackwitz|first=Ingolf|title=Zentralstadion Leipzig: vom Stadion der Hunderttausend zum Fussballtempel|publisher=Das Neue Berlin|year=2006|isbn=978-3360012807|location=|pages=15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Dieter Baroth|first=Hans|title=Als der Fussball laufen lernte: Tore, Triumphe, Tollheiten|publisher=Klartext|year=1992|isbn=978-3884744680|location=|pages=70}}</ref> The team also became a part of the Verband Leipziger Ballspiel Vereine on 30 March 1987, being the first team accepted into the federation after the initial founding members.<ref name=\":2\" /> Despite winning the last game of the 1899/1900 season against [[FC Wacker Leipzig]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.leipziger-fussballverband.de/cms2/index.php?page=152|title=1896 - 1899|last=|first=|date=10 February 2009|website=Leipziger Fussballverband|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leipziger-fussballverband.de/cms2/index.php?page=153|title=1900 - 1909|last=|first=|date=21 November 2010|website=Leipziger Fu\u00dfballverband|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>, they still placed at the bottom of the table for the second year in a row. All four founding members of this federation and Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig initially shared the [[Parade ground|Exerzierplatz]], formerly a military parade ground, in [[Rosenthal]]. Following the closure of the ground in 1899<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.speedskatingnews.info/en/data/rink/LPS/|title=Rink Card Of: Exerzierplatz Leipzig|last=|first=|date=|website=Speed Skating News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> the Sportplatz was instead used by the teams as a their playing ground. The other four teams using the ground were:\n\n* Leipziger Ballspiel-Club\n* FC Wacker Leipzig\n* VfB Leipzig\n* Abteilung Bewegungsspiele der Leipziger Finkenschaft.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n[[File:Leipzig - B\u00fcttnerstra\u00dfe - 10 01 ies oG.jpg|alt=German plaque outside Zum Marriengarten, which translates into English as \"Here, in the former 'Zum Marriengarten' restaurant, the German Football Association was founded on the 28 January 1900.\" Underneath this text is a inscription noting that the German Football Association and city of Leipzig put up this plaque on the 100th anniversary in the year 2000.|left|thumb|Plaque outside ''Zum Marriengarten'' which commemorates the founding of the German Football Association.|236x236px]]\nFollowing a meeting at the restaurant ''Zum Mariengarten,'' the same location where the German Football Association was founded, Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig merged with ''[[VfB Leipzig]]'' in 1898 to form ''VfB Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig''<ref name=\":0\" /> until the name was changed to the older VfB Leipzig on 2 November 1900.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dsc-museum.de/gegner/vfb-leipzig/|title=Verein f\u00fcr Bewegungsspiele Leipzig|last=|first=|date=|website=DSC Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/team/soccer/vfb-leipzig/561/|title=VfB Leipzig - Team Info|last=|first=|date=|website=Global Sports Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> This decision was encouraged by Thomas Sch\u00f6ffler<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schr\u00f6ter|first=Detlev|title=Camillo Ugi: Weltklassefu\u00dfballer|publisher=Engelsdorfer Verlag|year=2018|isbn=978-3961454006|location=|pages=10}}</ref> and proved to be of both personal and financial benefit for the teams.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe athletic department of ''Sportbr\u00fcder'' organized the country's first [[marathon]] on 5 September 1897 from [[Paunsdorf]] to [[Bennewitz]] and back, for which eighteen participants signed up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.speedskatingnews.info/en/results/?eventID=1864&gender=m|title=Competition: Wettlaufen des Clubs \"Sportbr\u00fcder\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Duwe|first=Klaus|title=42 mal 42: Marathon-Erlebnisse von Antalya bis Zermatt|publisher=Copress Sport|year=2008|isbn=978-3767910102|location=Germany|pages=77}}</ref> At 6 am the race began at Neuen Gasthof in Paunsdorf with Theodor Sch\u00f6ffler, a referee for VfB Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig and future founder of the German Football Association<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://germanroadraces.de/?p=58777|title=Der Leipzig Marathon \u2013 Stationen vom Elite- zum Volkslauf \u2013 die Geschichte des Laufes in 3 Folgen|last=|first=|date=9 December 2007|website=German Road Races|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>, being the first out of thirteen participants to cross the finish line at a time of 3:35:51. According to media reports, the race was received well by spectators.<ref name=\":5\" /> Another race took place the following year, but this time organised by the newly founded ''Deutschen Sportbeh\u00f6rde f\u00fcr Athletik (German Sports Authority for Athletics)''.<ref>\"[https://www.stadtgeschichtliches-museum-leipzig.de/fileadmin/user_upload/Konzept_Sportroute_final_Stand30072019.pdf Sportroute Leipzig\"] ''Stadtgeschichtliches Museum Leipzig'' Retrieved 9 April 2020.</ref> The athletic's division also had a prominent [[ice skating]] team.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nThe first national marathon championship in Germany was held in 1925 with the course beginning in [[Halle, Saxony-Anhalt|Halle]] and ending in [[Leipzig]] to commemorate the Sportbr\u00fcder athletics department's contribution to, and establishment of, the sport.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gottert|first=Frank|title=Marathon-Mekka Leipzig|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=9}}</ref> \n\n== Successors ==\nIt has sometimes been claimed that Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig completely separated from VfB Leipzig in 1900 and faded into obscurity<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundsinfocus.com/TT1011206.htm|title=Lokomotive Leipzig|last=|first=|date=21 March 2011|website=Football Grounds in Focus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>, but this belief is either due to a  possible misinterpretation of the German team ''Umbenennung'' (''renaming'') with reference to the change of VfB Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig to VfB Leizpig, or due to the departure of many, but not all, of the original Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig members.<ref name=\":4\" /> Under the name <nowiki>''VfB Leipzig''</nowiki> they enjoyed considerable success as one of the 86 founding clubs of the [[German Football Association]] and were the winners of the [[1903 German football championship|1903 German football championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wasistwas.de/details-sport-freizeit/wann-wurde-der-dfb-gegruendet-6793.html|title=Wann wurde der DFB gegr\u00fcndet?|last=|first=|date=|website=Was ist Was|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> At the founding of the German Football Association, under the name VfB Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig, they were represented by the chairman of the Federation of Leipzig Ballgame Teams [[Johannes Kirmse]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Spiel und Sport|date=3 February 1900|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|issue=444|edition=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Insolvency]] of VfB Leipzig at the end of 2004, [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]] claims to be the successor of the original Sportbr\u00fcder Leipzig and considers the team to be their \"founding fathers\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lok-leipzig.com/verein/geschichte/1893-1914-pionierarbeit-unter-der-pickelhaube/|title=Pionierarbeit Unter Der Pickelhaube (1893-1914)|last=|first=|date=|website=1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>, since they are seeking to purchase the defunct club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fussball.de/newsdetail/lok-leipzig-fusion-mit-vfb-ist-naeher-gerueckt/-/article-id/196244#!/|title=Lok Leipzig: Fusion mit VfB ist n\u00e4her ger\u00fcckt|last=|first=|date=28 November 2018|website=Fussball.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Should the deal go ahead, this would make them the nominal descendants of the team, but fans still consider the founding date of 1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig to be 1966 instead of 1893.\n== Results ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+As ''VfB'' ''Sportbr\u00fcder 1893 Leipzig''\n!Season\n!Competition\n!Result\n|-\n|1899/1900\n|Federation of Leipzig Ballgame Teams Championship\n|4th (last)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asc-neuenheim.de/ergebnisse/saison_1899-00/leipzig_1899.htm|title=Verband Leipziger Ballspiel Vereine 1899/00|last=|first=|date=|website=asc-neuenheim.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|1898/1899\n|Federation of Leipzig Ballgame Teams Championship\n|4th (last)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asc-neuenheim.de/ergebnisse/saison_1898-99/leipzig_1898.htm|title=Verband Leipziger Ballspiel Vereine 1898/99|last=|first=|date=|website=asc-neuenheim.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leipzig, Sportbruder}}\n[[Category:Football clubs in Germany]]\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in Germany]]\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in Saxony]]\n[[Category:Sport in Leipzig|Sportbruder]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1893]]\n[[Category:1893 establishments in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Allenthalben", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sportbr%C3%BCder_Leipzig"}
